<div dir="ltr"><div>btw, once it is at github, it can be the only repo with multiple access interfaces: svn,git</div><div> </div><div><a href="https://github.com/blog/1178-collaborating-on-github-with-subversion">https://github.com/blog/1178-collaborating-on-github-with-subversion</a></div>

<div> </div><div>Finally, we can commit from git or svn w/o keeping r/o mirrors for hg/git .....</div><div> </div><div>What do you think?</div><div><br><br> </div><div class="gmail_quote">On Fri, Aug 17, 2012 at 2:07 PM, Jeff Squyres <span dir="ltr">&lt;<a href="mailto:jsquyres@cisco.com" target="_blank">jsquyres@cisco.com</a>&gt;</span> wrote:<br>

<blockquote style="margin:0px 0px 0px 0.8ex;padding-left:1ex;border-left-color:rgb(204,204,204);border-left-width:1px;border-left-style:solid" class="gmail_quote">Come to think of it, why not host the official mercurial SVN mirror repo on Bitbucket for the same reason (lots of nice hg features on Bitbucket -- nicer than hgweb/<a href="http://www.open-mpi.org" target="_blank">www.open-mpi.org</a>&#39;s hosting).<br>


<br>
There&#39;s no need to delete the original mercurial SVN mirror on <a href="http://www.open-mpi.org" target="_blank">www.open-mpi.org</a> (because I know of at least one group who is actively using it), but we could deprecate it and schedule to take it down in, say, 6 months or so.<br>


